# Security-sensitive surfaces

Activate when editing auth, sessions, payments, PII, secrets, or access-control code.

## Input and boundary validation

- Validate all untrusted inputs at the boundary; do not trust upstream systems or internal callers.
- Use parameterized queries; never interpolate user data into SQL, shell commands, or templates.
- Sanitize and encode outputs; treat user-controlled content as untrusted in rendered output.

## Secrets and credentials

- No secrets, tokens, or credentials in code, logs, traces, error messages, or client-visible responses.
- Do not log sensitive values — not even partially (last 4 chars of a token is still a leak risk in some contexts).
- Environment variables or secret managers only; no hardcoded values.

## Auth / sessions

- Verify authentication before authorization checks — never assume caller identity.
- Regenerate session IDs after privilege changes (login, role escalation).
- Use short-lived tokens with server-side invalidation support.
- Validate token scope, audience (`aud`), and expiry on every request.

## Payments / PCI

- Tokenize card data; never log raw card numbers, CVVs, or PANs.
- Validate amounts and quantities server-side; never trust client-sent prices.
- Use idempotency keys on all mutation endpoints to prevent double-charges.

## Permissions and access control

- Apply least privilege — never widen access beyond what the current task requires.
- Treat permission changes and access widening as breaking changes requiring explicit review.
- Test both the authorized path and the unauthorized/forbidden path.

## Change discipline

- Auth, payment, and permission changes require explicit security review before merging.
- Do not silently absorb errors on security-critical paths — log (without sensitive data) and surface failures explicitly.
- Prefer reversible, auditable changes over silent defaults.
